idId><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE01982X%2F1"><gtr:id>841B708B-8CC1-4027-B4E1-3A846C5AA585</gtr:id><gtr:title>The economic ideas of Ernesto Che Guevara &amp;amp; their application in Cuba 1959-1965; a contribution to political economy and</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E01982X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Following the Revolution of 1959, Ernesto ?Che? Guevara worked in Cuba as President of the National Bank and Minister of Industries. He created an economic management system, adapting the productive and managerial techniques of capitalist multinationals to a Marxist theoretical framework to foster industry, increase productivity and institutionalise collective management. The challenge was to devise an apparatus for transition to socialism in conditions of underdevelopment which adopted advanced techniques but did not rely on capitalist levers: profit, competition, material incentives ? expressions of the law of value - that would undermine the formation of new consciousness and social relations integral to communism. &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>The research examines policies and development strategies formulated to meet this challenge. Based on new archival and interview sources, it assesses Guevara?s impact on Cuban economic development and industrial organisation from 1959-1965 and demonstrates how by 1964 Guevara?s analysis led him to conclude that the USSR was returning to capitalism. &lt;br />&amp;nbsp;&lt;br />The project objectives are: &lt;/p> 
&lt;ul> 
 &lt;li>To publish material from previous doctoral research&lt;/li> 
 &lt;li>To participate in establishing a Latin American political economy working group at ISA&lt;/li> 
 &lt;li>To preserve and archive the rich oral-history material collected in the field; and to strengthen links between ISA and academics and policy makers in Cuba&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li>
